		'Petroleo': 'How oil is formed',
		'TPetroleo': 'Petroleum is a fuel formed from sandstone or porous rocks that remain at the bottom of the oceans. So there are oil rigs to explore the fuel in various seas. ',
		'TPetroleo2': 'It has as its main characteristics its dark color, a viscous appearance and a strong smell. It is considered the number one source of energy generation in the world, making many countries highly dependent on this resource. In addition to being used as fuel, petroleum also gives rise to derivatives such as plastics, rubbers, fertilizers, paints and other Materials. ',
		'TPetroleo3': 'The initial stage of crude oil is called crude oil. It is the result of the accumulation of carbon-rich organisms in the bottom of the oceans. This matter has accumulated for thousands of years, trapped in a low-oxygen, sediment-filled environment.',
		'TPetroleo4': 'The petroleum formation process is slow and complex. In order for the fuel to form, the organic matter must be between 65 ° and 75 ° C and compressed by layers of sediment. Thus, it is necessary to have the ideal condition of pressure and heat for the fuel to form.',
		'fonte': 'Source:',
		'Estrelas': 'Why the stars shine',
		'TEstrelas':' The stars are huge reactors of nuclear fusion. The enormous amount of mass they have causes the gravitational force to be immense, which in turn increases the pressure and temperature, to the point of the gas that forms the stars to enter into a nuclear fusion reaction.',
		'TEstrelas2': 'Sun-like stars are turning hydrogen into helium. Other larger stars perform other types of fusion, so that all the elements you see around you once were in a star nucleus - we are all star dust. ',
		'TEstrelas3': "And when helium is formed by the fusion of hydrogen, there is also the release of a lot of energy in the form of electromagnetic radiation, and in several bands, among which we usually call' light '. Stars are gigantic furnaces of nuclear fusion, and produce helium, light and heat.",
		'Lendas': 'The most famous legends in the world',
		'TLendas': "Urban legends have been part of the children's and adult imagination for a long time. They have replaced, in a way, the folk legends from the woods and forests. As in the modern world almost no one has contact with nature and its myths, other stories were created from the lifestyle of big cities.",
		'TLendas2': 'The most famous in the world is the Loch Ness Monster, perhaps the most well-known urban legend and also one of the oldest. Its cradle is Scotland, where there is a belief in a terrible monster living in the depths of Loch Ness. One of the first reports was made in 1933 by a couple who claimed to have seen a 9-meter-long, dark-gray animal with a snake-like head. To this day one hears stories about new apparitions, but no one has ever been able to prove conclusively.',
		'TLendas3': 'Other examples of urban legends are: Big Foot, The Abominable Snowman and the Witch of the Mirror.',
		'Idiomas': 'The 5 languages ​​of antiquity not yet deciphered',
		'TIdiomas':' 1. The Proto-Elamita ',
		'TIdiomas2': '2. The Harapano ',
		'TIdiomas3': '3. The Meroítico ',
		'TIdiomas4': '4. The Linear A ',
		'TIdiomas5': '5. The Cipro-Minoico ',
		'TIdiomasT': 'The Proto-Elamite language is one of the earliest writing systems in history, and was used for about 5,000 years in territories that now correspond to Iran. Most of the surviving Is in the Louvre Museum in France and a few years ago an initiative focused on digitizing existing texts was put into action so linguists around the world could have access to the material to try to decipher the language.',
		'TIdiomasT2':'Developed by the Indus Valley civilization, which flourished some 4,000 years ago in the region that today comprises Pakistan, India, Iran and Afghanistan, the Harapan language consists of a series of symbols that, to this day, have not Were translated. Thousands of objects containing characters of this writing have already been discovered, however, in the absence of a copy written in two languages ​​- one of them already known by linguists - it remains indecipherable.',
		'TIdiomasT3': 'The language was developed by the inhabitants of the Kingdom of Kush, whose headquarters were in the ancient city of Meroe in Sudan, and remained in use between 300 BC and 350 AD, more or less. According to what is known about this language, it was written in cursive form and in hieroglyphs, both derived from ancient Egyptian, but although linguists have deciphered what the symbols of that language represent, they can not quite understand the structure of the Texts, which makes its translation difficult. ',
		'TIdiomasT4': 'Created by the Minoan Civilization, which flourished in Crete between 2500 and 1450 BC, the language known as Linear A was a writing system discovered during excavations in the ancient city of Knossos about a century ago. Curiously, there is a language called Linear B that has already been deciphered and possibly derived from A, but to date the alphabet used in Linear A remains a mystery to linguists.',
		'TIdiomasT5': 'Widely used in Cyprus between the 16th and 11th centuries BC, the Cipro-Minoan syllabary - also known as Linear C - has never been deciphered by linguists. One of the reasons for this is that there are only about 200 texts, many of them quite short, which makes translation difficult. Unless a bilingual copy is discovered, it is possible that this language will never be understood. ',
		'Cirugia': 'How surgery was done centuries ago',
		'TCirugia': 'Going to the hospital in the early 19th century was almost a death sentence, those who had money were treated and operated in their homes. Therefore, those who were unlucky enough to end up in the operating room of a hospital such as St. Thomas, one of the oldest in London, had a high probability of dying of an infection. they:',
		'TCirugia2': 'The most common was that they died from post-operative infections, but to minimize the chances of death from bleeding, surgeons of the time operated as fast as they could, lasting about 10 to 15 minutes, The fast doctors became more famous according to the speed of their procedures.',
		'TCirugia3': 'In 1822 patients felt unimaginable pain during the operations, which were done on a small wooden stretcher. At that time, the richest patients, attended by the doctors in their homes, took alcohol to decrease the pain in the procedures . However, women who passed through the Old Operating Theater received only a leather-coated bat to bite during surgery. In some cases the patients were blindfolded, but in general they watched everything.',
		'TCirugia4': 'Like other anatomical dissection and surgical rooms that existed at the time in Europe, it had a kind of bleachers and semicircular grilles to facilitate the visibility of the public, which was composed mainly of medical students, apprentices and assistants The presence and position of the members of the public was regulated and was common in all operating rooms of the time - in the center, were the surgeon and his helpers, who held the patient so that he would not move during the surgery.',
		'TCirugia5': 'At the time, doctors and scientists believed that contagious diseases were caused by the miasma - bad smell of the streets and rivers, which dissipated through the air - and not by microorganisms. Therefore, no antiseptic method was used in the operating room. The blood of the operations was collected in a wooden box with sawdust or sand, and the surgeons and their assistants only washed their hands after the operations, and not before.',
